# migrated from tests/cases/reflexive_compose.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test reflexive_compose]
# gen164/gen165 (E1 reflexive): parrot0 reasons about composing its OWN parts.
# The gen160 self-challenge probe walled here; now a composition self-challenge —
# varied surface, held-out — lands in mod_loop with a loop-shaped METHOD (the
# compose-bench discipline), staying anti-self-management (propose, never act).
# gen165: the three named parts are DERIVED from the live module(X) self-model
# (the same fact base "who is a module?" reads), not a fixed triple — knowledge,
# abduce and robust, exactly the parts tests/compose/analytical_en.dlg proves
# cooperate.
> how would you prove that your subsystems compose, not just work alone?
< I would treat it as a composition self-challenge, not self-management: from my own module set I would pick three parts I actually have — knowledge (facts and rules), abduction (the missing premise), and robustness (which facts are load-bearing) — and write ONE held-out dialogue, with fresh names so it cannot be memorized, that needs all three at once; it passes only if they cooperate with no new special-case module. I would ratchet it in English and Italian, bump my version, and journal whether composition held or a seam appeared. I can propose this; an external agent edits, runs the tests, and commits.
> what should change to test composition over three subsystems?
< I would treat it as a composition self-challenge, not self-management: from my own module set I would pick three parts I actually have — knowledge (facts and rules), abduction (the missing premise), and robustness (which facts are load-bearing) — and write ONE held-out dialogue, with fresh names so it cannot be memorized, that needs all three at once; it passes only if they cooperate with no new special-case module. I would ratchet it in English and Italian, bump my version, and journal whether composition held or a seam appeared. I can propose this; an external agent edits, runs the tests, and commits.
> design a test where three of your parts work together
< I would treat it as a composition self-challenge, not self-management: from my own module set I would pick three parts I actually have — knowledge (facts and rules), abduction (the missing premise), and robustness (which facts are load-bearing) — and write ONE held-out dialogue, with fresh names so it cannot be memorized, that needs all three at once; it passes only if they cooperate with no new special-case module. I would ratchet it in English and Italian, bump my version, and journal whether composition held or a seam appeared. I can propose this; an external agent edits, runs the tests, and commits.
